<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="249" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="38.[136,1452,1742,1985]" box="[136,583,1742,1768]" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,292,1742,1768]" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">Distribution:</emphasis>
— 
<collectingCountry box="[320,406,1742,1768]" name="Guyana" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">Guyana</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[461,580,1742,1768]" name="Venezuela" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[136,1452,1742,1985]" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,294,1778,1804]" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">Notes:—</emphasis>
This species has been reported from only 
<collectingCountry box="[759,846,1778,1804]" name="Guyana" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">Guyana</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[899,1018,1778,1804]" name="Venezuela" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
. It is caespitose with slender ramicauls and narrow leaves producing successive single flowers. The habit is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ames &amp; Schweinfurth" authorityYear="1930" box="[1020,1197,1814,1840]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Pleurothallis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="38" pageNumber="249" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hirsuticaulis">
<emphasis box="[1020,1197,1814,1840]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">M. hirsuticaulis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luer" authorityYear="1982" baseAuthorityName="Luer" baseAuthorityYear="1976" box="[1252,1360,1815,1840]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Myoxanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="38" pageNumber="249" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="merae">
<emphasis box="[1252,1360,1815,1840]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">M. merae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the yellowish to brownish flowers with abaxially shortly pubescent sepals are most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luer" authorityYear="1982" baseAuthorityName="Luer" baseAuthorityYear="1976" box="[1171,1280,1851,1876]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Myoxanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="38" pageNumber="249" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="merae">
<emphasis box="[1171,1280,1851,1876]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">M. merae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is only found in 
<collectingCountry box="[241,334,1886,1912]" name="Ecuador" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[392,447,1887,1913]" name="Peru" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">Peru</collectingCountry>
. It is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Luer" authorityYear="1982" baseAuthorityName="Luer" baseAuthorityYear="1976" box="[735,844,1887,1912]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Myoxanthus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="38" pageNumber="249" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="merae">
<emphasis box="[735,844,1887,1912]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="249">M. merae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the wider petals with a more pronounced narrow, thickened apical section, more pronounced and oblique lateral lobes of the lip and a pair of longitudinal calli emerging below the middle of the lip extending to the base.
</paragraph>
